d Kingdom","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Hopton and Griff-Grange, Derbyshire, England":"Hopton and Griff-Grange, Derbyshire, England","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gyles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Giles  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giles","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from a medieval personal name, Middle English <i>Giles</i> or <i>Gile</i>, a borrowing from Old French <i>Gil(l)e(s)</i>. This is from Latin <i>Aegidius</i> and this presumably from Greek <i>aigidion</i> ‘kid, young goat’ (alternatively, it could be a Late Latin formation from the Latin personal name <i>Eggius</i> + the suffix <i>-idius</i>). The personal name was widely used in France and the Low Countries, partly through veneration of Saint Gilles de Provence, supposedly a hermit of the 7th century near Arles; he was patron saint of cripples, hence the dedication of Saint Giles Cripplegate in London, though the personal name itself was less common in England than elsewhere in Europe. See also   Gilles  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Glaisne</b>, a County Louth name based on <i>glas</i> ‘green, blue, gray’.","French: variant of   Gilles  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":59,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":68,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Thyrkyll Gyles II was born in 1490, in Suffolk, England, his father, John Gyles IV, was 30 and his mother, Margery de Blackwell, was 25. He married Lady Elizabeth Ann Wiggs about 1514, in Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1568, in his hometown, at the age of 78, and was buried in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1490–1568":"1490–1568","1491–1564":"1491–1564","1493–Female":"1493–Surnud","–1535":"–1535","–1579":"–1579","–Female":"Surnud","1492–Female":"1492–Surnud","1517–1595":"1517–1595","1460–1521":"1460